#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:73
msgid ""
"In the Edit Marker window you can enable :guilabel:`Range Marker` which "
"allows you to determine a :guilabel:`Duration` of the marker. Default :"
"guilabel:`Duration` is 1 second."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:77
msgid "You can create a marker with range from a clip zone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:85
msgid "Make sure you select the desired clip in the project bin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:89
msgid ""
"Define a zone in the clip monitor with :kbd:`I` and :kbd:`O`. Then you can:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:91
msgid ""
"Right click on the zone and choose :guilabel:`Create Marker from Zone`. This "
"opens a window (see above) and you can adjust all settings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:93
msgid ""
"Right click on the zone and choose :guilabel:`Create Marker from Zone "
"Quickly`. This creates a marker with the text :guilabel:`Zone Marker` in the "
"currently active category."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:95
msgid ""
"Now the advantage is, that you can select this zone marker in the markers "
"windows and drag it to the timeline. In this way you can mark interesting "
"parts of a clip with zone marker instead of :ref:`Insert Zone in Project Bin "
"<insert_zone_in_project_bin>` and creating sub clips."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:100
msgid "Managing categories and markers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:105
msgid "Categories"
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:107
msgid ""
"Markers using the same categories as :ref:`guides`. More details about :ref:"
"`categories`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:110
msgid "Markers in the clip monitor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:112
msgid ""
"Once markers are put in your clip, you can access them in the :ref:`ui-"
"monitors_clip_monitor` by right-clicking and selecting :menuselection:`Go To "
"Marker` or by the hamburger menu :menuselection:`Go To Marker` (see "
"picture).  Also note how the markers appear as vertical lines according the "
"category color you have chosen (see yellow highlighted regions in the "
"picture). You can turn on the display of the marker comments in the timeline "
"too (see :ref:`editing`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:120
msgid "Markers View"
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:122
msgid ""
"Markers are using the same window as :ref:`timeline marker <guide_view>`. "
"Yellow markings show the differences compared to the guide view."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:127
msgid ""
":menuselection:`View --> Markers` opens the markers window where you can "
"manage your markers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:129
msgid "To show clip markers in this view you have to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:131
msgid ""
"Project bin: click on the desired clip and the markers of the clip show up "
"in the window."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:133
msgid ""
"On the timeline: right click on the desired clip and choose :menuselection:"
"`Clip in Project Bin` and the markers of this clip show up in the window."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:135
msgid "The complete description of the view see :ref:`guide_view`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../cutting_and_assembling/markers.rst:138
msgid ""
"You can put a comment in the marker and make the comment display by "
"choosing :ref:`editing` in the :menuselection:`Timeline` menu or by clicking "
"on the :ref:`editing` button."
msgstr ""

